Disclaimer- I have had this rifle up for months, I have received responses from outside of the state and folks that are not willing to meet up. I will not ship, I will not deliver unless arrangements are made. We can meet locally in Ellensburg and or we can meet half way (make an arrangement) Local sales only, will not budge.

PICTURES TOO LARGE- PLEASE EMAIL FOR MORE PHOTOS (I HAVE PHOTOS OF THE RIFLE FROM ALL ANGLES, WITH SCOPE ON AND OFF)

Russian Capture- Czech manufactured (DOU) 1944 on receiver. Imported by Century, with import marks underneath the barrel (so older import, as I am told they got in trouble with ATF and now have to put import marks on receiver and in easily spotted areas) This rifle being a capture rifles was rebuilt by the russians and has no original matching parts except electropencil after rebuild (much like a mosin nagant). The rifle has the original marksman style safety (to clear a scope) and has been drilled for scope rings. The scope rings are high turret reproductions (valued at $100-200 depending on what size, height, on various mauser outfits). I will throw in a redfield scope (NOT ORIGINAL, NOT REPRODUCTION, MODERN Style Scope). 

I bought the rifle with the scope and rings, but have been firing it using iron sights, bore is good and shoots straight. I have a few 8mm surplus rounds (14) remaining that I will throw in as well. 

The Nazi Swastikas have been removed, but the eagles remain (Russians removed all swastikas during the re-arsenal) pictured is what is left of the swastika. There are various ones located all over the rifle.

title: For Sale:  Mossberg 590, 9 shot, surefire pump, optics, mesa tactical, blackhawk stock
postcontent:
One Mossberg 590 shotgun. This is the heavy 9 shot model, with a slightly modified bayonet lug to reduce metal on metal contact with the bezel of the flashlight. Dual locking bars, massively thick barrel and magazine tube, and Picatinny standard rail makes this shotgun one of the best scatterguns in the world. Used by the U.S. Marines, it can accept mossberg 500 parts like stocks, magazine tubes, barrels, and forends. Not sure why you would, but you could if you wanted. It is chambered for 2 3/4 loads, and considering it is a pump gun, it will reliably feed every sort of 12 gauge shells you could possibly want. 
One Surefire Dedicated Forend light, with pressure switch and a bezel typical of surefire weaponlights. The grip area is tactile rubber, and the body is metal. This model is the high end one, including a two battery body, constant on/off switch, and a weaponlight lockout switch to keep it from turning on when you don't want it. 
One Mesa Tactical side saddle shell carrier. It bolts securely to the frame of the gun, through the rear takedown pin and the ejector bolt. there is a thin strip of rubber beneath it, so your frame is still unmarred after hundreds of rounds of buckshot. There is an internal tube of replaceable rubber (just replaced) that holds the rounds in. Don't worry about primers pointed down, this holds shells solidly. 
One Blackhawk recoil control stock. while expensive, it includes an internal recoil reduction spring, pistol grip, and M4 style rear stock. Sling attachment points in three places, a rubber buttpad, and an internal locking grommet keeps everything very solid. 
One optics rail, designed for this weapon specifically. while Picatinny standard, the inside has a groove to allow you to use the iron sights. Not sure why you would, though. The stock is directly inline with the barrel, making it very controllable, but not so great for using the front bead. 
One Sig Sauer red dot optic. uses 2032 batteries, with ten levels of brightness. Its locktited onto the rail, so it would be tough to remove, but again, why would you want to? 

All together, this is a combat scattergun that would be right at home in a patrol car, home defense safe, or war zone. you would be hard pressed to find accessories better than what you are buying, and you would pay far more to build it. 

The gun is solid, with minor wear and tear, but upkeep, cleaning, and parts replacement has been monitored by an active duty Army armorer. The ejector, magazine spring, and rubber sidesaddle tube have been replaced within the last six months, and it comes with a free, brand new magazine tube spring. 

Sadly, the primary user of this fine firearm has swapped to a different model due to work requirements, so now it is up for grabs.
